body:
Current, `AddSeqMemPorts` will error if you have a situation where a memory is instantiated under the design-under-test (DUT) and above it. This is typically avoided by `LowerMemories` which is both responsible for creating `firrtl.memmodule` and only deduplicating memories that are under the DUT. However, if a memory like this leaks through, then it can cause an error.

Consider the following circuit:

``` mlir
firrtl.circuit "Foo" attributes {
  annotations = [
    {
      class = "sifive.enterprise.firrtl.AddSeqMemPortAnnotation",
      name = "user_input",
      input = true,
      width = 1
    }
  ]
} {
  firrtl.layer @A bind {}

  firrtl.memmodule @mem(
    in W0_addr: !firrtl.uint<1>,
    in W0_en: !firrtl.uint<1>,
    in W0_clk: !firrtl.clock,
    in W0_data: !firrtl.uint<1>
  ) attributes {
    dataWidth = 1 : ui32,
    depth = 2 : ui64,
    extraPorts = [],
    maskBits = 1 : ui32,
    numReadPorts = 0 : ui32,
    numReadWritePorts = 0 : ui32,
    numWritePorts = 1 : ui32,
    readLatency = 1 : ui32,
    writeLatency = 1 : ui32
  }

  firrtl.module @Bar() attributes {
    annotations = [
      {class = "sifive.enterprise.firrtl.MarkDUTAnnotation"}
    ]
  } {
    %0:4 = firrtl.instance mem @mem(
      in W0_addr: !firrtl.uint<1>,
      in W0_en: !firrtl.uint<1>,
      in W0_clk: !firrtl.clock,
      in W0_data: !firrtl.uint<1>
    )
  }

  firrtl.module @Foo() {
    firrtl.instance bar @Bar()
    %0:4 = firrtl.instance mem @mem(
      in W0_addr: !firrtl.uint<1>,
      in W0_en: !firrtl.uint<1>,
      in W0_clk: !firrtl.clock,
      in W0_data: !firrtl.uint<1>
    )
  }

}
```

When compiled with `circt-opt -firrtl-add-seqmem-ports Foo.mlir  | circt-opt` this will not update the instance that is outside the DUT. It is additionally unclear how it could update this memory.

```
<stdin>:13:5: error: 'firrtl.module' op block argument locations should match signature locations
    "firrtl.module"() ({
    ^
<stdin>:13:5: note: see current operation: 
"firrtl.module"() ({
^bb0(%arg0: !firrtl.uint<1>):
  %0:5 = "firrtl.instance"() {annotations = [], layers = [], moduleName = @mem, name = "mem", nameKind = #firrtl<name_kind droppable_name>, portAnnotations = [[], [], [], [], []], portDirections = array<i1: false, false, false, false, false>, portNames = ["W0_addr", "W0_en", "W0_clk", "W0_data", "user_input"]} : () -> (!firrtl.uint<1>, !firrtl.uint<1>, !firrtl.clock, !firrtl.uint<1>, !firrtl.uint<1>)
  "firrtl.matchingconnect"(%0#4, %arg0) : (!firrtl.uint<1>, !firrtl.uint<1>) -> ()
}) {annotations = [{class = "sifive.enterprise.firrtl.MarkDUTAnnotation"}], convention = #firrtl<convention internal>, layers = [], parameters = [], portAnnotations = [[{class = "firrtl.transforms.DontTouchAnnotation"}]], portDirections = array<i1: false>, portLocations = [loc(unknown)], portNames = ["sram_0_user_input"], portSyms = [], portTypes = [!firrtl.uint<1>], sym_name = "Bar"} : () -> ()
```

This could be solved with memory duplication. I will plan to add a stopgap error that will prevent generating illegal MLIR. The best solution is to delete this pass entirely and move the functionality of this pass (MBIST insertion) into Chisel.
